Psoriasis is driven by TH17 cells secreting IL-17A and IL-22, which:
1. IL-17A stimulates keratinocyte proliferation via NF-κB and ERK pathways, inducing antimicrobial peptides (e.g., β-defensin-2) and chemokines (CXCL1, CCL20);
2. IL-22 activates STAT3 in keratinocytes, upregulating anti-apoptotic genes (Bcl-xL), S100 proteins, and filaggrin suppression;
3. Synergistically, these cytokines promote neutrophil infiltration and vascular remodeling.
Biologics target:
- IL-17A: secukinumab (inhibits receptor binding), brodalumab (blocks IL-17RA);
- IL-23: ustekinumab (p40 subunit), risankizumab (p19 subunit), which reduces TH17 differentiation;
- JAK-STAT: tofacitinib (JAK1/3 inhibitor) blocks IL-22 signaling.
Clinically, IL-17 inhibitors achieve PASI90 in 70% of patients (vs. 40% with methotrexate). In sum, TH17 cytokines orchestrate psoriasis via keratinocyte-T cell crosstalk, with targeted biologics achieving unprecedented clearance rates.

