Syncytiotrophoblast vesicles (STBVs), released from the placental surface, carry PD-L1 and indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase (IDO):
1. PD-L1 on STBVs binds PD-1 on maternal T cells, inducing Treg differentiation (FOXP3+, IL-10+);
2. STBVs secrete IDO, catabolizing tryptophan into kynurenine, which:
   - Depletes tryptophan (limiting T-cell proliferation);
   - Generates kynurenine metabolites that activate AhR on maternal dendritic cells, promoting IL-10 secretion;
   - Suppresses MAIT and NKT cells via aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR) activation.
This creates a semi-allogeneic immune privilege, preventing fetal rejection. In preeclampsia, reduced STBV PD-L1/IDO correlates with immune activation (aberrant Th17 cells). Therapeutically, STBV infusions in mouse models reduce fetal loss by 60% (Nat Commun 2023). In sum, STBVs orchestrate immune tolerance through metabolic and checkpoint pathways, essential for fetal survival.

