NODDI models diffusion MRI data to separate:
1. Intracellular volume fraction (ICVF, neurite density);
2. Orientation dispersion index (ODI, axonal bending/tortuosity);
3. Free water fraction (FWF, edema/lesion core).
In MS plaques, NODDI reveals:
- Reduced ICVF in T2 lesions (axon loss);
- Elevated ODI in normal-appearing white matter (NAWM, early demyelination);
- Increased FWF in acute gadolinium-enhancing lesions (edema).
Compared to conventional DWI, NODDI detects microstructural changes prior to T2 hyperintensity, with 85% sensitivity for early MS (Radiology 2024). Clinically, NODDI correlates with EDSS scores (r=0.72) and predicts disability progression (AUC 0.81). In summary, NODDI provides quantitative biomarkers for MS microstructural damage, enabling earlier diagnosis and treatment monitoring.

