ECMO exposes blood to non-biologic surfaces, triggering:
1. Shear stress–induced VWF unfolding, exposing A1 and A2 domains;
2. Platelet GPIbα binding to VWF A1, causing transient aggregation and exhaustion;
3. ADAMTS13 cleavage of ultra-large VWF multimers, but shear-mediated proteolysis overwhelms this system.
Additionally, heparin anticoagulation inhibits thrombin-mediated platelet activation, exacerbating bleeding. Clinically, ECMO patients have:
- Reduced VWF:RCo activity (30% of baseline);
- Elevated VWF propeptide levels (markers of endothelial damage);
- Increased bleeding risk (OR 2.4 vs. non-ECMO ARDS).
Therapeutically, plasma exchange to replenish ADAMTS13 or VWF concentrates (e.g., in VWF disease) are under investigation (NCT05181332). In sum, ECMO-induced VWF-platelet axis dysregulation underlies coagulopathy, requiring targeted hemostatic interventions.

